---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
const baseUrl = import.meta.env.BASE_URL.replace(/\/$/, "");
---

<Base title="Required Data Maturity">
  <p class="back-link">
    <a href={baseUrl || "/"}>← Back to landscape</a>
  </p>

  <header class="about-hero" style="--accent:#5b8def">
    <span class="hero-icon" aria-hidden="true">
      <svg viewBox="0 0 24 24" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="1.7" stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round">
        <path d="M12 2 L4 6 V12 C4 17 8 21 12 22 C16 21 20 17 20 12 V6 Z" />
        <path d="M8.5 12 l2.3 2.3 4.7 -4.7" />
      </svg>
    </span>
    <h1>Required Data Maturity</h1>
    <p class="hero-tag">The Y axis: how much clean, structured data the approach needs.</p>
  </header>

  <article class="about-body">
    <p>
      In data science, a familiar saying is that 80% of the work is data
      preparation. AI in security is no different. Two use cases with similar
      business value can have very different total cost of ownership, simply
      because one needs months of data plumbing before it produces anything
      useful, and the other works on data you already have.
    </p>
    <p>
      The Y axis captures that effort. From bottom to top, each band needs
      progressively more <em>data maturity</em>: not just volume, but also
      quality, labelling, and standardisation.
    </p>

    <h2>The five bands</h2>

    <h3>Reinforcement Learning <span class="muted">(bottom — data-lean)</span></h3>
    <p>
      Learns by interacting with an environment, not by being trained on a
      labelled corpus. Useful for adaptive policy tuning and bypass
      simulations — but constrained to settings where you can simulate the
      environment safely.
    </p>

    <h3>Unsupervised Learning</h3>
    <p>
      Finds structure in data without labels: anomaly detection, clustering,
      noise reduction. Excellent when you have lots of raw telemetry but no
      ground-truth examples of "bad".
    </p>

    <h3>Semi-Supervised Learning</h3>
    <p>
      A small set of labels plus a large unlabelled dataset. Practical when
      labelling is expensive but you can hand-curate a few hundred examples
      to bootstrap the model.
    </p>

    <h3>Supervised Learning</h3>
    <p>
      Trained on labelled examples. Classic ML — incident classification,
      risk scoring, phishing prediction. Demands a clean, labelled dataset
      that mirrors what you'll see in production.
    </p>

    <h3>Large Language Models <span class="muted">(top — data-rich)</span></h3>
    <p>
      Pre-trained on huge corpora; you mostly bring context (RAG), prompts,
      or fine-tuning data. The model is data-rich by default — the question
      becomes how well-organised <em>your</em> domain context is.
    </p>

    <p class="callout">
      <strong>Why this matters:</strong> the higher up the Y axis, the more
      time you'll spend on data infrastructure (pipelines, embeddings,
      governance) before you see results. Pick approaches that match what
      you already have, then climb deliberately.
    </p>
  </article>
</Base>

<style>
  .back-link {
    margin: 0 0 1rem;
    font-size: 0.9rem;
  }

  .about-hero {
    display: flex;
    flex-direction: column;
    align-items: center;
    text-align: center;
    gap: 0.5rem;
    padding: 2rem 1rem 1.5rem;
    background: color-mix(in srgb, var(--accent) 10%, var(--bg-elevated));
    border: 1px solid var(--border);
    border-top: 4px solid var(--accent);
    border-radius: 12px;
    margin-bottom: 2rem;
  }

  .hero-icon {
    width: 56px;
    height: 56px;
    color: var(--accent);
  }

  .hero-icon svg {
    width: 100%;
    height: 100%;
  }

  .about-hero h1 {
    margin: 0.25rem 0 0;
    font-size: 1.8rem;
  }

  .hero-tag {
    margin: 0;
    color: var(--text-muted);
    max-width: 50ch;
  }

  .about-body {
    max-width: 70ch;
    margin: 0 auto;
    font-size: 1rem;
    line-height: 1.65;
  }

  .about-body h2 {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    font-size: 1.2rem;
  }

  .about-body h3 {
    margin-top: 1.5rem;
    margin-bottom: 0.25rem;
    font-size: 1rem;
  }

  .muted {
    color: var(--text-muted);
    font-weight: 400;
    font-size: 0.88em;
  }

  .callout {
    margin-top: 2rem;
    padding: 1rem 1.1rem;
    background: var(--bg-elevated);
    border-left: 3px solid #5b8def;
    border-radius: 4px;
  }
</style>
